1
00:00:06,034 --> 00:00:08,254
Who are you?

2
00:00:08,842 --> 00:00:11,753
[A. Stanton]: 
That was the theme—
who are you.

3
00:00:12,013 --> 00:00:15,009
A strong theme is always running
through a well-told story.

4
00:00:15,329 --> 00:00:19,479
[An Inconceivable Story]

5
00:00:19,835 --> 00:00:23,529
We all love stories,
we’re born for them.

6
00:00:23,529 --> 00:00:25,288
Stories are from who we are.

7
00:00:25,288 --> 00:00:27,758
We all want affirmations
that our lives have meaning.

8
00:00:27,893 --> 00:00:34,123
[Goswami Mj]: We’re riveted to story,
we are hardwired for story.

9
00:00:34,322 --> 00:00:38,442
That’s why to this day
what’s been handed down in time,

10
00:00:38,442 --> 00:00:43,968
when we say ‘story’, we mean 
a narrative about who are people,

11
00:00:43,968 --> 00:00:48,421
what is our purpose,
what is our prospect or our possibilities.

12
00:00:48,421 --> 00:00:51,298
And different stories 
speak to that.

13
00:00:51,298 --> 00:00:54,441
That’s why human beings 
are storytellers.

14
00:00:54,441 --> 00:00:57,584
Animals are not storytellers.

15
00:00:57,584 --> 00:00:59,757
Someone will try to say, 
“No, but dogs,

16
00:00:59,757 --> 00:01:04,141
they dream about catching cats
or cats dream about catching mice.”

17
00:01:04,141 --> 00:01:06,474
That’s another thing.

18
00:01:06,474 --> 00:01:10,483
Dealing with base necessities:
eating, sleeping, sex, defense.

19
00:01:10,483 --> 00:01:14,017
Human beings, 
they’re interested in story

20
00:01:14,017 --> 00:01:17,103
that speaks to their heart
and their identity potential.

21
00:01:17,263 --> 00:01:20,291
As parents you are always learning
who your children are.

22
00:01:20,291 --> 00:01:22,165
They’re learning 
who they are.

23
00:01:22,165 --> 00:01:24,234
And you’re still learning
who you are.

24
00:01:24,234 --> 00:01:26,669
So we are all learning
all the time.

25
00:01:26,669 --> 00:01:29,768
And that is why change
is fundamental in story.

26
00:01:29,768 --> 00:01:33,852
If things go static, stories die
because life is never static.

27
00:01:34,022 --> 00:01:40,334
One of the famous axioms
or maxims of writing

28
00:01:40,334 --> 00:01:42,132
is show, don’t tell.

29
00:01:42,322 --> 00:01:45,462
We would call this 
the unifying theory of 2+2.

30
00:01:45,462 --> 00:01:46,426
[Unifying Theory of 2+2]

31
00:01:46,426 --> 00:01:48,165
Make the audience
put things together.

32
00:01:48,165 --> 00:01:50,997
Don’t give them 4,
give them 2+2.

33
00:01:51,197 --> 00:01:54,547
The good writers,
they write things in such a way

34
00:01:54,547 --> 00:01:58,504
that you get the picture, 
so to speak.

35
00:01:58,504 --> 00:02:03,738
They don’t tell you exactly what it is,
they show what it is by

36
00:02:03,738 --> 00:02:08,618
to get heady and intellectual;
T.S. Elliot called “the objective correlative”.

37
00:02:08,796 --> 00:02:13,661
Which means, whatever 
the author has in mind,

38
00:02:13,661 --> 00:02:15,711
there’s an objective correlative,

39
00:02:15,711 --> 00:02:18,350
meaning words, images, etc.

40
00:02:18,350 --> 00:02:20,524
that if they are assembled
in a proper way,

41
00:02:20,524 --> 00:02:23,254
will convey that idea
or concept to the person.

42
00:02:23,524 --> 00:02:27,478
I don’t mean to make it sound
like this is an actual exact science.

43
00:02:27,478 --> 00:02:28,311
It’s not.

44
00:02:28,311 --> 00:02:31,949
That’s what’s so special about stories,
they’re not a widget.

45
00:02:31,949 --> 00:02:33,133
They aren’t exact.

46
00:02:33,133 --> 00:02:36,379
Stories are inevitable, if they’re good,
but they’re not predictable.

47
00:02:36,379 --> 00:02:40,640
The story of God is inconceivable.

48
00:02:40,640 --> 00:02:45,870
The story of science, of rational,
appears to be believable

49
00:02:45,870 --> 00:02:48,794
to the so-called 
rational mind.

50
00:02:48,794 --> 00:02:53,154
But the story of God 
is inconceivable.

51
00:02:53,236 --> 00:02:57,115
Of the two we prefer
the inconceivable story of God

52
00:02:57,115 --> 00:03:00,470
to the rational, the so-called 
rational narrative

53
00:03:00,470 --> 00:03:04,850
of secular humanist 
and atheistic science.

54
00:03:04,850 --> 00:03:08,574
[E. Core]: I have always felt
that one of the greatest gifts of mankind

55
00:03:08,574 --> 00:03:10,225
is not the opposable thumb,

56
00:03:10,225 --> 00:03:12,735
which has given us technology
in our society,

57
00:03:12,735 --> 00:03:14,915
but the ability to tell story.

